{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e6a014da-6cc0-45c5-8e34-ab89a42646a9","content":"Neither — use **`dotnet watch test`**.\n\n- `dotnet test` runs tests once and exits; no hot reload.\n- `dotnet run` is for running applications, not test projects.\n- **`dotnet watch test`** watches for file changes and automatically re-runs your tests, giving you the hot-reload-style feedback loop.\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test --project TestProject.csproj\n```\n\nThe `DOTNET_WATCH_RESTART_ON_RUDE_EDIT=1` environment variable (if that's what you set) ensures it restarts cleanly when edits can't be applied in-place.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1230d825-c513-4dc2-9bc0-854df4fb8785","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to benefit from hot reload in .NET testing. Let me look at the files in the current directory to understand the context better.","outputTokens":197,"requestId":"CFD8:1D248C:1605C93:197F2DC:69EC197B"},"id":"3227fd93-e2eb-4052-897c-a9c5e06dcc8b","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:31:45.348Z","parentId":"230ccd3a-0eac-4ca6-ba81-6c2170160557"}
